  "answers" : [ {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 262293,
      "reputation" : 5758,
      "user_id" : 547065,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/3ca7b22b90c1506277b6f7ead24eb21c?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Vladislav Vaintroub",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/547065/vladislav-vaintroub"
    },
    "is_accepted" : true,
    "score" : 5,
    "last_activity_date" : 1696069637,
    "last_edit_date" : 1696069637,
    "creation_date" : 1687467783,
    "answer_id" : 76535643,
    "question_id" : 76519029,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>It is usually <a href=\"https://mariadb.com/kb/en/server-system-variables/#net_write_timeout\" rel=\"noreferrer\">net_write_timeout</a> . Server closes the socket, if your application is not reading data as fast as the server writes them. net_write_timeout defines, in seconds, how long server can stuck trying to send the result set. You can increase that limit, it is a session variable. This also appears in the MariaDB JDBC's  <a href=\"https://mariadb.com/kb/en/about-mariadb-connector-j/#error-could-not-read-resultset-unexpected-end-of-stream-read-0-bytes-from-4\" rel=\"noreferrer\">FAQ</a></p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 10064309,
      "reputation" : 305,
      "user_id" : 7439920,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/d983a5dbc5f8c35610eb542b0d4922fd?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "S. Parton",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/7439920/s-parton"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 0,
    "last_activity_date" : 1751354313,
    "creation_date" : 1751354313,
    "answer_id" : 79685652,
    "question_id" : 76519029,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>My case had nothing to do with a stored procedure, but the &quot;unexpected end of stream&quot; message instantly disappeared, when I killed an &quot;htop&quot;-Session running through another SSH-connection to a server I used for tunneling my DB connection. So also look out for these kinds of connection issues when you see that error message.</p>\n"
  } ],
